[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hit
<hw>Hit</hw>, <def><pos>3d pers. sing. pres.</pos> of <er>Hide</er>,
contracted from <xex>hideth</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Hit
<hw>Hit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Hit</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Hitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>hitten</ets>,
<ets>hutten</ets>, of Scand. origin; cf. Dan. <ets>hitte</ets> to hit,
find, Sw. & Icel. <ets>hitta</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To reach
with a stroke or blow; to strike or touch, usually with force;
especially, to reach or touch (an object aimed at).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I think you have <qex>hit</qex> the mark.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To reach or attain exactly; to meet according to the
occasion; to perform successfully; to attain to; to accord with; to be
conformable to; to suit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Birds learning tunes, and their endeavors to <qex>hit</qex> the
notes right.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There you <qex>hit</qex> him; . . . that argument never fails with
him.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose saintly visage is too bright⟦br⟧
To <qex>hit</qex> the sense of human sight.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He scarcely <qex>hit</qex> my humor.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To guess; to light upon or discover.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Thou hast <xex>hit</xex> it.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Backgammon)</fld> <def>To take up, or replace by a
piece belonging to the opposing player; -- said of a single unprotected
piece on a point.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hit off</b></col>, <cd>to describe with quick
characteristic strokes; as, <xex>to hit off</xex> a speaker.</cd>
<au>Sir W. Temple.</au> -- <col><b>To hit out</b></col>, <cd>to perform
by good luck.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Spenser.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Hit
<hw>Hit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To meet or
come in contact; to strike; to clash; -- followed by <xex>against</xex>
or <xex>on</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If bodies be extension alone, how can they move and <qex>hit</qex>
one against another?</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Corpuscles, meeting with or <qex>hitting</qex> on those bodies,
become conjoined with them.</q> <rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To meet or reach what was aimed at or desired; to
succeed, -- often with implied chance, or luck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And oft it <qex>hits</qex>⟦br⟧
Where hope is coldest and despair most fits.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And millions miss for one that <qex>hits</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>To hit on</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To hit
upon</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to light upon; to come to by chance; to
discover unexpectedly; <as>as, he <ex>hit on</ex> the solution after
days of trying</as>.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧None of them <xex>hit upon</xex> the
art.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Addison.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Hit
<hw>Hit</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A striking against; the
collision of one body against another; the stroke that touches
anything.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So he the famed Cilician fencer praised,⟦br⟧
And, at each <qex>hit</qex>, with wonder seems amazed.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stroke of success in an enterprise, as by a
fortunate chance; <as>as, he made a <ex>hit</ex></as>;</def>
<specif>esp.</specif> <def>A performance, as a musical recording, movie,
or play, which achieved great popularity or acclaim; also used of books
or objects of commerce which become big sellers; <as>as, the new
notebook computer was a big <ex>hit</ex> with business
travellers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>What late he called a blessing, now was wit,⟦br⟧
And God's good providence, a lucky <qex>hit</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A peculiarly apt expression or turn of thought; a
phrase which hits the mark; <as>as, a happy <ex>hit</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A game won at backgammon after the adversary has
removed some of his men. It counts less than a
<contr>gammon</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <def>A striking of the ball;
<as>as, a safe <ex>hit</ex>; a foul <ex>hit</ex></as>; -- sometimes used
specifically for a <altname>base hit</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An act of murder performed for hire, esp. by a
professional assassin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Base hit</b></col>, <col><b>Safe hit</b></col>,
<col><b>Sacrifice hit</b></col></mcol>. <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Base</er>, <er>Safe</er>, etc.</cd></cs></p>

<p><ent>Hit.</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Hit.
<hw>Hit.</hw> <pos>adj.</pos> <def>Having become very popular or
acclaimed; -- said of entertainment performances; <as>as, a <ex>hit</ex>
song, a <ex>hit</ex> movie</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hitch</ent>⟦br⟧
